Valuation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Refresh a company's financials and details quarterly.
 
\series default
Peter Lynch - every few months it's worthwhile to recheck the company story.
 This may involve reading latest analysis or quarterly reports, and inquiring
 about the earnings and whether the earnings are holding up as expected.
 With fast growers, especially, you have to ask yourself what will keep
 them growing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's start with Aswath Damodaran, a Professor of Finance at New York University
, where he teaches corporate finance and equity valuation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Value rests on standard ingredients: cash flows, growth and risk, though
 the effects of each vary across companies and across time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
No matter what type of company you are valuing, you have to decide whether
 you are valuing just equity or the entire business, the approach you will
 use to estimate value (intrinsic versus relative valuation), and the key
 components of value.
 If you value the business, you can get to the value of equity by adding
 back assets that you have not valued yet (cash and cross holdings) and
 subtracting out what you owe (debt).
 The choice matters because all of your inputs - cash flows, growth, and
 risk - have to be defined consistently.
 Aswath Damodaran valued the businesses and backed into the value of equity.
 With financial service firms, our inability to define debt and estimate
 cash flows push us into using equity valuation models.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Well done valuations based upon better information should generate better
 returns than shoddy valuations based upon rumor or worse.
 The second is market feedback.
 To make money on even the best-done valuation, the market has to correct
 its mistakes.
 In more selfish terms, you want the market to be efficient for the most
 part, with pockets of inefficiency that you can exploit.
 There is also a factor of luck.
 While this will violate your sense of fairness, luck can overwhelm good
 valuation skills.
 While you cannot depend on good luck, you can reduce the impact of luck
 on your returns by spreading your bets across many companies that you have
 found to be undervalued.
 Diversification still pays.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Growth is not free and is not always good for value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All good things, including growth, come to an end.
 Nothing is forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Look at the past but think about the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Remember the law of large numbers.
 An average is better than a single number.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Accept uncertainty, face up to it and deal with it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
If you cannot analyze/valuate a company and/or cannot predict what will
 happen with its business in the future, skip the given business and find
 one you can figure out.
 Because otherwise you are just guessing - there is nothing wrong with some
 guessing, but make conservative guesses.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Convert stories to numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Valuation gives you a lifevest, that's all what it is.
 It gives you something to hold on to when everybody else changes their
 mind and go another direction.
 It's not gonna stop you from doing really stupid things - if you really
 want to buy something, you'll find a way to buy it.
 The same for selling.
 Valuation slows the process down.
 It gives you rationale side of the argument.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Most people don't believe in valuation (even ones whose use valuation for
 living).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Three rules of valuation:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Valuation is simple.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Every valuation has a story, a narrative behind it; a good valuation is
 more about the story that it is about the numbers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
When valuations go bad it's not because of the numbers, it's because of
 3 problems: bias (wrong assumptions we made), uncertainty, and complexity
 (of the world and models).
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
If you see someone else's valuation, you have to check who did it and who
 paid for it.
 Another thing it that when you do a valuation, you are using numbers.
 But they are estimates.
 There is a great deal of uncertainty.
 They are always gonna be wrong.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
All valuations are biased.
 You almost never start valuing a company or stock with a blank slate.
 All too often, your views on a company or stock are formed before you start
 inputting the numbers into the models and metrics that you use and, not
 surprisingly, your conclusions tend to reflect your biases.
 Confine your background research on the company to information sources
 rather than opinion sources; in other words, spend more time looking at
 a company's financial statements than reading equity research reports about
 the company.
 If you are looking at someone else's valuation of a company, always consider
 the reasons for the valuation and the potential biases that may affect
 the analyst's judgments.
 As a general rule, the more bias there is in the process, the less weight
 you should attach to the valuation judgment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Most valuations (even good ones) are wrong.
 One thin is estimation error, about the future of a business, which is
 firm-specific uncertainty, resulting in earnings and cash flows will be
 different from your estimates.
 Finally, even if a firm evolves exactly the way you expected it to, the
 macroeconomic environment can change in unpredictable ways.
 Also, collecting more information and doing more analysis will not necessarily
 translate into less uncertainty.
 In some cases, ironically, it can generate more uncertainty.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Smaller models are better.
 Complex models are black boxes - are you running a model or a model is
 running you? Complex models got lots of numbers - garbage in, garbage out.
 If you can valuate company with 3 numbers, don't use fourth.
 Less is more.
 Simpler can be better.
 Valuations have become more and more complex over the last two decades,
 as a consequence of two developments.
 Computers and calculators are more powerful and accessible than they used
 to be, making it easier to analyze data.
 On the other side, information is both plentiful and easier to access and
 use.
 More detail gives you a chance to use specific information to make better
 forecasts, but it also creates the need for more inputs, with the potential
 for error on each one, and it generates more complicated and opaque models.
 When valuing an asset, use the simplest model that you can.
 If you can value an asset with 3 inputs, don't use 5.
 If you can value a company with three years of forecasts, forecasting 10
 years of cash flows is asking for trouble.
 Less is more.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Don't stop trying.
 Most investors choose not to value companies and offer a variety of excuses:
 valuation models are too complex, there is insufficient information, or
 there is too much uncertainty.
 While all of these reasons have a kernel of truth to them, there is no
 reason why they should stop you from trying.
 Valuation models can be simplified and - yes - the future will always be
 uncertain.
 Will you be wrong sometimes? Of course, but so will everyone else.
 Success in investing comes not from being right but from being wrong less
 often than everyone else.
\end_layout

