Capital Asset Pricing Model (CAPM)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Developed in early 1960s.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In this model, you assume that investors face no transaction costs and share
 the same information.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Since there is no cost to diversifying and no gain from not doing so, each
 investor holds a supremely diversified portfolio composed of all traded
 assets (called the market portfolio).
 The risk of any asset then becomes the risk added to this "market portfolio",
 which is measured with a beta.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The beta is a relative risk measure and it is standardized around 1; a stock
 with a beta above 1 is more exposed to market risk than the average stock,
 and below 1 is less exposed.
 The expected return on the investment can then be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
risk_free_rate + beta * (risk_premium_for_average_risk_investment) 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
