\begin_layout Itemize
The debt factor.
 How much does the company owe, and how much does it own? Debt versus (stockhold
er's) equity.
 A normal corporate balance sheet has 75% equity and 25% debt.
 Weak balance sheet might have 80% debt and 20% equity.
 Especially among turnarounds and troubled companies, Lynch pays special
 attention to the debt factor.
 It's debt that determines which companies will survive and which will go
 bankrupt in a crisis.
 Young companies with heavy debts are always at risk.
 Also, it's the kind of debt as much as the actual amount, that separates
 the winners from the losers in a crisis.
 There's bank debt and there's funded debt.
 Bank debt is the worst kind, and is due on demand.
 It doesn't have to come from a bank.
 It can also take the form of commercial paper, which is loaned from one
 company to another for short periods of time.
 The important thing is that it's due very soon, and sometimes even "due
 on call".
 That means that the lender can ask for his money back at the first sign
 of trouble.
 If the borrower can't pay back the money, it can be very dangerous to sharehold
ers.
 Funded debt is the best kind, from shareholder's point of view, and it
 can never be called in no matter how bleak the situation, as long as the
 borrower continues to pay the interest.
 The principal may not be due for 15, 20, or 30 years.
 It usually takes the form of regular corporate bonds with long maturities.
 Corporate bonds may be upgraded or downgraded by the rating agencies depending
 on the financial health of the company, but whatever happens, the bondholders
 cannot demand immediate repayment of principal the way a bank can.
 Sometimes even interest payments can be deferred.
 Funded debt gives companies time to wiggle out of trouble.
\end_layout

