\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Time is Money
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The simplest tools in finance are often the most powerful.
 The notion that a dollar today is preferable to a dollar in the future
 is intuitive enough for the most people to grasp without the use of models
 and mathematics.
 The principles of present value enable us to calculate exactly how much
 a dollar sometime in the future is worth in today's terms, and to compare
 cash flows across time.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are 3 reasons why a cash flow in the future is worth less than a similar
 cash flow today:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
People prefer consuming today to consuming in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Inflation decreases the purchasing power of cash over time.
 A dollar in the future will buy less than a dollar would buy today.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
A promised cash flow in the future may not be delivered.
 There is risk in waiting.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
The process by which future cash flows are adjusted to reflect these factors
 is called discounting, and the magnitude of these factors is reflected
 in the discount rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The discount rate can be viewed as a composite of the expected real return
 (reflecting consumption preferences), expected inflation (to capture the
 purchasing power of the cash flow), and a premium for uncertainty associated
 with the cash flow.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The process of discounting converts future cash flows into cash flows in
 today's terms.
 There are 5 types of cash flows - simple cash flows, annuities, growing
 annuities, perpetuities, and growing perpetuities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A simple cash flow is a single cash flow in a specified future time period.
 Discounting a cash flow converts it into today's dollars (or present value)
 and enables the user to compare cash flows at different points in time.
 The present value of a cash flow is calculated as:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
cash_flow_in_future_period / (1 + discount_rate) ^ time_period
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
An annuity is a constant cash flow that occurs at regular intervals for
 a fixed period of time.
 While you can compute the present value by discounting each cash flow and
 adding up the numbers, you can also use this equation:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
annual_cash_flow * ((1 - 1/(1+discount_rate)^number_of_periods) / discount_rate)
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A growing annuity is a cash flow that grows at a constant rate for a specified
 period of time.
 The formula is similar to the one above:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
cash_flow(1+g) * ((1 - ((1+g)^n / (1+r)^n )) / (r-g))
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
you can also arrive at the same number by computing the present value of
 each cash flow and adding up the numbers.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A perpetuity is a constant cash flow at regular intervals forever and the
 present value is obtained by dividing the cash flow by the discount rate.
 The most common example offered for a perpetuity is a console bond, a bond
 that pays a fixed interest payment (or coupon) forever.
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
the value of a console bond that pays $60 coupon each year, if the interest
 rate is 9% is as follows: $60/0.09=$667
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
A growing perpetuity is a cash flow that is expected to grow at a constant
 rate forever.
 The present value of a growing perpetuity can be written as:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
expected_cash_flow_next_year / (discount_rate - expected_growth_rate)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Although a growing perpetuity and a growing annuity share several features,
 the fact that a growing perpetuity lasts forever puts constraints on the
 growth rate.
 The growth rate has to be less than the discount rate for the equation
 to work, but an even tighter constraint is that the growth rate used has
 to be lower than the nominal growth rate of the economy, since no asset
 can have cash flows growing faster than that rate forever.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For example, assume that you are assessing a stock that paid $2 as dividends
 last year.
 Assume that you expect these dividends to grow 2% a year in perpetuity,
 and that your required rate of return for investing in this stock, given
 its risk, is 8%.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
$2 * 1.02 / (0.08 - 0.02) = $34
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
These cash flows are the essential building blocks for virtually every financial
