\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
Risk
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Cash flows that are riskier should be assessed a lower value than more stable
 cash flows.
 In conventional discounted cash flow valuation models, we use higher discount
 rates on riskier cash flows and lower discount rates on safer cash flows.
 The definition of risk will depend upon whether you are valuing the business
 or just the equity.
 When valuing the business, you look at the risk in a firm's operations.
 When valuing equity, you look at the risk in the equity investment in this
 business, which is partly determined by the risk of the business the firm
 is in and partly by its choice on how much debt to use to fund that business.
 The equity in a safe business can become risky, if the firm uses enough
 debt to fund that business.
 In discount rate terms, the risk in the equity in a business is measured
 with the cost of equity, whereas the risk in the business is captured in
 the cost of capital.
 The latter will be weighted average of the cost of equity and the cost
 of debt, with the weights reflecting the proportional use of each source
 of funding.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
There are 3 inputs needed to estimate a cost of equity:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Risk-free rate - described below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Equity risk premium (ERP) - described below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relative risk or beta - we generally look at how much a stock has moved
 in the past, relative to the market.
 So beta is always backward looking and noisy.
 One solution is to replace the regression beta with a sector-average beta,
 if the firm operates in only one business or a weighted average of many
 sector betas if the firm operates in many businesses.
 The sector beta is more precise than an individual regression beta because
 averaging across many betas results in averaging out your mistakes.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
The risk free rate
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Some people use government bond rate - US Treasury Bond rate for instance.
 It's not that simple though.
 To really get something that's risk-free, you first have to make sure that
 the entity issuing the security has no default risk.
 It is not easy to do in some parts of the world.
 It can be different in different currencies.
 But for USD, you can use 10- or 30-year government bonds rates as risk-free
 rate, implicitly assuming that governments don't default.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For an investment to be risk-free, it has to have no default risk and no
 reinvestment risk.
 Also, time horizon matters - if your cash flows stretch out over the long
 term, your risk free rate has to be a long term risk free rate.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When you do valuation, it can be in nominal terms (reflect expected inflation),
 or real terms (ignoring inflation) - nominal/real cash flows.
 If your cash flows are nominal cash flows, what currency you're going to
 do the cash flows - the currency becomes an issue only with nominal cash
 flows.
 You can value any company in any currency.
 Once you pick the currency in which you're going to estimate the cash flows,
 your discount rate has to be exactly in that currency.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The cost of equity - should be higher for riskier investments and lower
 for safer investments.
 There are many models to calculate this: CAPM (you need risk free rate,
 beta relative to market portfolio, and market risk premium), APM (as CAPM,
 but it's a little more creative in measuring market risk - rather than
 capture all with 1 beta, this allows to input multiple sources of market
 risk and allow for beta for each one), Multifactor (this includes also
 macro factors - interest rates, inflation, etc), Proxy (it takes the last
 20 years, especially if we have access to more data; you don't measure
 risk in traditional way; instead, it's measured for example - smaller companies
 are riskier than large cap companies, or we can use also other proxies;
 the proxy models can be an add on to traditional models.
 You often see composite models - where you measure beta as a risk and a
 proxy thrown to the model).
 For all of those models, you need a risk-free rate.
\end_layout

