Growth Rates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When confronted with the task of estimating growth, it is not surprising
 that analysts turn to the past, using growth in revenues or earnings in
 the recent past as a predictor of growth in the future.
 However, the historical growth rates for the same company can vary, depending
 upon computational choices: how far back to go, which measure of earnings
 (net income, earnings per share, operating income) to use, and how to compute
 the average (arithmetic or geometric).
 Studies indicate that the relationship between past and future growth for
 most companies is a very weak one, with growth dropping off significantly
 as companies grow and revealing significant volatility from period to period.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
For a firm to grow, it has to either manage its existing investments better
 (efficiency growth) or make new investments (new investment growth).
 To capture efficiency growth, you want to measure the potential for cost
 cutting and improved profitability.
 It can generate substantial growth in the near term, especially for poorly
 run mature firms, but not forever.
 To measure the growth rate from new investments, you should look at how
 much of its earnings a firm is reinvesting back in the business and the
 return on these investments.
 The way we'll look at these two terms will depend upon whether we are looking
 at equity earnings or operating income.
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
With equity earnings, we measure reinvestment as the portion of net income
 not paid out as dividends (retention ratio) and use the return on equity
 to measure the quality of investment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
With operating income, we measure reinvestment as the reinvestment rate
 and use the return on capital to measure investment quality.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
For estimating growth, you can:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Look at the past at the historical growth at EPS is a good starting point
 check how it is calculated - arithmetic (tend to be higher) vs geometric
 average, operating income, revenues, ...
 etc check estimation period - starting point for the computation can make
 a big difference recognize that growth rates become meaningless when earnings
 go from negative to positive values recognize that growth rates will go
 down as companies get larger.
 Worst of all, there is an evidence that historical growth rates in earnings
 are not very good predictors of future earnings.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
See what analysts are estimating - they estimate growth in EPS and it is
 useful to know what their estimates are; management forecasts can be biased,
 because they cannot be objective.
 Analysts forecasts are mostly focused on short term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Estimate it by yourself - look at fundamentals - how much the firm is investing
 in new projects and what returns these projects are making for the firm.
 Growth has to be earned by a company.
 
\end_layout

