 Relative valuation outnumbers DCF valuation (even when someone is doing
 DCF and using multiples for calculating terminal value, even that can be
 considered as a relative valuation).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Relative valuations are far easier to sell than intrinsic valuations, because
 as long as you let me pick the multiple and comparables, I can tell you
 whatever story I want to tell you.
 And also it's far easy to defend a relative valuation than an intrinsic
 valuation - in intrinsic valuation your assumptions are all explicit -
 everybody can see what you're assuming about cash flows, growth, and risk,
 and that's dangerous because they can pick it apart.
 In relative valuation, all you assumptions are implicit - when you are
 using 12 times EBIDTA, you are making assumptions, but nobody can see what
 those assumptions are.
 If they cannot see them, they cannot pick them apart.
 Aswath Damodaran thinks that in the long term you are far more likely to
 be right with intrinsic valuation than relative valuation, but here's the
 catch - when you're wrong with intrinsic valuation, you are also far more
 likely to be wrong alone = fired.
 Survival instinct.
 That's why more people are using relative valuation.
\end_layout

