\begin_layout Subsubsection
Aswath Damodaran on Relative Valuation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Assets are valued by looking at how the market prices similar assets.
 Thus, when determining what to pay for a house, you would look at what
 similar houses in the neighborhood sold for.
 With a stock, that means comparing its pricing to similar stocks, usually
 in its "peer group".
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It's all about comparing how the market prices different companies, with
 the intent of finding bargains.
 In relative valuation, you value an asset based on how similar assets are
 priced in the market.
 There are 3 essential steps:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Find comparable assets that are priced by the market.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Scale the market prices to a common variable to generate standardized prices
 that are comparable across assets.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Adjust for differences across assets when comparing their standardized values.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Relative valuation can be done with less information and more quickly than
 intrinsic valuation and is more likely to reflect the market mood of the
 moment.
 Not surprisingly, most valuations that you see are relative.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
