\begin_layout Subsection
Option Pricing Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Not for valuing options, but businesses.
 Real option advocates a belief that you should be paying a premium on DCF
 value estimates.
 This is not an alternative to DCF, it is its augmentation.
 For every hundred options, maybe two or three will pass the following tests
 you gotta meet to applying these models to valuing an asset:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You gotta make sure that there is an option embedded in an action.
 Can you identify the underlying asset? Can you specify the contingency
 under which you will get payoff?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Is there exclusivity? If yes, there is option value.
 If no, there is none.
 If in between, you have to scale value.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Can you use an option pricing model to value the real option? Can you trade
 the underlying asset and option?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Applying option pricing models in the context of valuation - this is being
 used only if something happens.
 For example, there is an undeveloped oil reserve company, and those oil
 reserves will have value only if oil prices go up beyond a certain level.
 Or a gold mining company with gold reserves.
 Or a biotechnological company with the patent that's not viable right now
 but potentially viable in the future.
 Or a stock of a deeply troubled company - a money-losing company with a
 lot of debt - you are effectively buying an option.
 These are examples of where you can apply this model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You are using those option pricing models to value businesses or assets
 that have option like characteristics.
 Options derive the value from an underlying asset.
 They have contingent payoff and limited life.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

