\series default
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
It makes restrictive assumptions about volatility (fixed over option life)
 and early exercise (none) and price process for underlying asset.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The model is a function of 6 parameters:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
current price of the underlying asset
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
strike price of the option
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
life of the option
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
variance in the price often underlying assets
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
risk-less rate for the option life
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
dividends over the life of the option (not in original model)
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Warren Buffett uses the Black-Scholes formula when valuing his equity put
 options for financial statement purposes.
 Key inputs to the calculation include a contract's maturity and strike
 price, as well as the analyst's expectations for volatility, interest rates
 and dividends.
 However, if the formula is applied to extended time periods (for long-dated
 options), it can produce absurd results.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\series bold
\emph on
The Binomial Option Pricing Model
