\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Simple Moving Average (SMA)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
Moving average of the stock's price and smooths out the bounciness of the
 raw price so you can better detect its trend.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The position of the current price in relation to the SMA provides hints
 on where the price is heading next.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
A price line's relationship to its SMA shows you its trend.
 If the price is staying above the SMA at a rising angle, that's rising
 trend, or uptrend.
 If the price is staying below the SMA at a falling angle, that's a falling
 trend, or downtrend.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The easiest way to get buy and sell hints from this measure is to watch
 for when the investment's price line crosses above or below its SMA.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
When the investment is moving up, the SMA acts as a support line, and the
 price dipping below the line and moving back up signals a buy.
 When the investment is moving down, the SMA acts as a resistance line,
 and the price popping above the line and moving back down signals a sell.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Many traders use several moving averages together, such as a 20-day, 50-day,
 and a 200-day and watch for them to cross over each other for hints on
 future price direction.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize

\emph on
Moving Average Convergence Divergence (MACD)
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
It compares the exponential moving average of a stock's price from two time
 periods, usually 12 and 26 days or weeks or months, and then plots that
 difference to show a trend.
 MACD is similar to SMA, but it places more weight on recent prices than
 on past ones, making it react more quickly to trend changes.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The MACD message is comprised of three parts:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Itemize
MACD - the 12-period exponential moving average minus the 26-period.
 This is the difference between 
